### Company or project name
ClickHouse
### Describe the situation
When using the `merge()` function or table engine, queries that use an `WHERE <partial PK> ORDER BY <primary key> LIMIT 1` are slower than expected compared to querying the table directly.
### Which ClickHouse versions are affected?
25.4 at least
### How to reproduce
```
CREATE TABLE users (uid Int16, name String, age Int16, time Int8, PRIMARY KEY(time, age, name) ) ENGINE=MergeTree;
INSERT INTO users VALUES (1231, 'Ksenia', 33, 2);
INSERT INTO users VALUES (6666, 'Ksenia', 48, 2);
INSERT INTO users VALUES (8888, 'John', 50, 2);
EXPLAIN PLAN actions=1 SELECT name FROM default.users WHERE time > 1 ORDER BY time, age LIMIT 1;
EXPLAIN PLAN actions=1 SELECT name FROM merge('default', '^users$') WHERE time > 1 ORDER BY time, age LIMIT 1;
```
Fiddle: https://fiddle.clickhouse.com/6026e24d-964e-49ab-bc97-9a1f75ba3287
### Expected performance
I would expect that the `ReadType` would be `InOrder` for the `merge` function. If I omit the `Where`, it uses a `ReadType` `InOrder`, and reading the table directly also allows the ReadType to be InOrder.
